xv6 Project 1B: Process Info, Blocking, and Resource Usage System Calls
======================================================================

MODIFIED FILES
--------------
  kernel/proc.h      - Added struct proc_info, struct resource_usage,
                       enum procstate_extra (BLOCKED/UNBLOCKED), and new
                       per-process counter fields in struct proc.

  kernel/proc.c      - Initialized new fields in freeproc() and allocproc().
                       Modified scheduler() to skip BLOCKED processes.
                       Added sleepCount increment in sleep().
                       Added contextSwitches increment in scheduler().
                       Implemented blockchild() and unblockchild() at end of file.

  kernel/trap.c      - Added syscallCount increment in usertrap() when a
                       system call is detected (r_scause() == 8).
                       Added cpuTicks increment in usertrap() when a timer
                       interrupt fires (which_dev == 2).

  kernel/syscall.h   - Added system call numbers:
                         SYS_getprocinfo     = 22
                         SYS_blockchild      = 23
                         SYS_unblockchild    = 24
                         SYS_getresourceusage = 25

  kernel/syscall.c   - Declared extern handlers for all four new syscalls.
                       Registered them in the syscalls[] dispatch table.
                       Implemented sys_blockchild() and sys_unblockchild()
                       wrappers (arg extraction + kernel function call).

  kernel/sysproc.c   - Implemented sys_getprocinfo(): fills proc_info struct
                       from current process's PCB and copies to user space.
                       Implemented sys_getresourceusage(): copies resource
                       counters from PCB to user space, returns caller's PID.

  kernel/defs.h      - Added forward declaration for struct resource_usage.
                       Declared blockchild(), unblockchild(), and
                       getresourceusage() for cross-file linkage.

  user/usys.pl       - Added entry() calls for getprocinfo, blockchild,
                       unblockchild, and getresourceusage to generate
                       the assembly stubs that invoke the ecall instruction.

  user/user.h        - Added struct proc_info and struct resource_usage
                       definitions (must match kernel-side exactly).
                       Added declarations for all four new system calls.


DESIGN CHOICES
--------------

Task 1 – getprocinfo
  The proc_info structure is defined in both kernel/proc.h and user/user.h
  with identical layout so that copyout() transfers the data correctly.
  The system call simply reads fields directly from myproc() (the calling
  process's PCB) with no locking needed for its own fields, since a process
  cannot race with itself. The parent PID is read under the assumption that
  wait_lock is not required here because we only read p->parent->pid
  (a stable integer) and the project runs with CPUS=1.

Task 2 – blockchild / unblockchild
  Rather than introducing a new main process state (which would require
  changes throughout the scheduler and sleep/wakeup paths), a secondary
  field state_extra (enum procstate_extra) was added to struct proc.
  This keeps the change minimal and isolated: only the scheduler loop in
  scheduler() needs a one-line guard to skip processes where
  state_extra == BLOCKED.

  Both blockchild() and unblockchild() are placed at the end of proc.c
  because they need direct access to the global proc[] array. Each acquires
  the target process's spinlock before reading or modifying state, following
  standard xv6 locking conventions. The functions reject:
    - Processes that are not direct children of the caller
    - UNUSED or ZOMBIE processes (cannot be meaningfully blocked)
    - Double-block or double-unblock requests (idempotency avoided by design,
      per spec: these should return -1)

  A blocked process that is SLEEPING will eventually wake up (via wakeup())
  and transition to RUNNABLE, but the scheduler will not dispatch it until
  unblockchild() clears the BLOCKED flag. This is intentional: the block
  acts as a scheduling gate, not a sleep mechanism.

Task 3 – getresourceusage
  Four counters are stored directly in struct proc and zeroed in freeproc():
    cpuTicks        – incremented in usertrap() on each timer interrupt
                      (which_dev == 2) while the process is in user mode.
    syscallCount    – incremented in usertrap() each time r_scause() == 8,
                      before syscall() is dispatched.
    contextSwitches – incremented in scheduler() immediately before swtch(),
                      counting each time the process is given the CPU.
    sleepCount      – incremented at the top of sleep(), before the process
                      changes state, counting voluntary sleeps only.

  getresourceusage() copies these four values into a user-space struct and
  returns the caller's PID, matching the specification.


KNOWN LIMITATIONS
-----------------
  1. CPUS=1 assumed throughout. No additional locking was added around the
     new counter increments (cpuTicks, syscallCount, etc.) because with a
     single CPU, only one process runs at a time and no concurrent updates
     are possible. On a multi-CPU build these would be data races.

  2. blockchild() does not force a sleeping child out of sleep. If a child
     is blocked while it is in the SLEEPING state, it will eventually wake
     and transition to RUNNABLE, but then be held at the scheduler gate. A
     blocked-while-sleeping child will not print or execute user code, but
     it will consume a slot in the wakeup scan.

  3. struct proc_info and struct resource_usage are duplicated between
     kernel/proc.h and user/user.h. If either definition changes, both must
     be updated manually. xv6 has no shared include mechanism between kernel
     and user space.

  4. syscallCount is incremented in usertrap() before syscall() runs, so it
     counts every system call invocation including failed or invalid ones.
     This matches the spec ("each invocation counts once"), but means the
     counter reflects dispatch attempts, not successful completions.

  5. contextSwitches counts scheduler selections, not preemptions. A process
     preempted by a timer interrupt is yielded back to RUNNABLE and re-
     selected on the next scheduling round, so one preemption results in two
     contextSwitches increments (the selection before the preemption, and the
     re-selection afterward).